05014nam a22011415i 9780691239446DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20211995nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912394467 a10.1515/97806912394462doi  a(DE-B1597)612827  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43/09441 aAndrew, Dudley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMists of Regret :bCulture and Sensibility in Classic French Film /cDudley Andrew. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b132 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJust before World War II, French cinema reached a high point that has been dubbed the style of "poetic realism." Working with unforgettable actors like Jean Gabin and Arletty, directors such as Renoir, Carné, Gremillon, Duvivier, and Chenal routinely captured the prizes for best film at every festival and in every country, and their accomplishments led to general agreement that the French were the first to give maturity to the sound cinema. Here the distinguished film scholar Dudley Andrew examines the motivations and consequences of these remarkable films by looking at the cultural web in which they were made. Beyond giving a rich view of the life and worth of cinema in France, Andrew contributes substantially to our knowledge of how films are dealt with in history. Where earlier studies have treated the masterpieces of this era either in themselves or as part of the vision of their creators, and where certain recent scholars have reacted to this by dissolving the masterpieces back into the system of entertainment that made them possible, Andrew stresses the dialogue of culture and cinema. In his view, the films open questions that take us into the culture, while our understanding of the culture gives energy, direction, and consequence to our reading of the films. The book demonstrates the value of this hermeneutic approach for one set of texts and one period, but it should very much interest film theorists and film historians of all sorts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAcademic publishing.  aAlbert Lamorisse.  aAmerican Philosophical Association.  aAnti-realism.  aBibliography.  aCase study.  aClaire Fox.  aEdition (book).  aExploration.  aFellow.  aFor Children (Bartók).  aForay.  aFrancesco Casetti.  aGenre.  aIllustration.  aJean Mitry.  aJean Renoir.  aJeu.  aLa Tosca.  aLibrary of Congress.  aMargaret Herrick Library.  aMathematics.  aMichael Dummett.  aMichel Simon.  aModernity.  aMonograph.  aNational Endowment for the Humanities.  aNational cinema.  aNazi Party.  aNew York Public Library for the Performing Arts.  aOxymoron.  aPaperback.  aPelican Books.  aPhotography.  aPoetic realism.  aPoetry.  aPreface.  aPrinceton University Press.  aPrinting.  aPublication.  aRapport.  aScience book.  aSensibility.  aSocial environment.  aThe Possibilities (Preacher).  aTheatrical adaptation.  aTheory.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691239446zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691239446423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691239446/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK